or), who both sit on the SCC Transport</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Forum</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A Voluntary Car</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Scheme Partnership exists in the district which is attended by SCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and local community transport providers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  This group feeds into Transport in Somerset </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Community Transport Forum </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">meetings twice a year.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">To what extent are the needs of different group</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">f passengers taken into account in determining the provision of public transport to isolated communities?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">West Somerset district is spread over 740 square kilometres with 0.45 people per hectare making the area one of the most sparsely populated in the co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">untry.  Rural residents</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> have an increased pressure as they have </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to travel further for services </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">plus</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> challenges with regard to accessibility by road to key services and employment centres, especially via foot and public transport.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  More than one in five peo</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ple in West Somerset live beyond the ‘reasonable’ limit for accessing key services via public transport, with the exception of hospitals and primary schools.  Only 26% of residents live where they can either walk or get public transport to access their</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> loc</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">al</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> town centre. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Young people find it difficult to access evening employment, studies or social activities as there is limited public transport often finishing to early.  Many older people who do not have their own transport rely on community transport to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> take them to and from hospital appointments, though they struggle to attend </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">any </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">social functions due to the lack of volunteer drivers for the community car schemes.  Accessible Transport West (ATWest) </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">provides</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a minibus service which can accommodate peopl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e with wheelchairs and other physical needs</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of clients</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What are the main challenges associated with providing better and more consistent bus and rail services to isolated communities?  How can these challenges be overcome?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are no mainline rail </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">links in West Somerset; the closest mainline station is Taunton.  A heritage steam railway operates a tourist service along a 20 mile track between Minehead and Bishop Lydeard.  The track is connected to the mainline at Taunton but is used very infrequentl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">y for tourist services.  There would be potential to bring a commuter rail service into West Somerset with sufficient finances – reducing the traffic and CO</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:7pt">2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> emissions on the busy A358.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There is one viable bus service which runs between Minehead and Taunt</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on.  All other public transport services in West Somerset are subsidised.  SCC is considering axing many of these services in the future to reduce their costs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ont</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d..</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">To our knowledge no mapping of the present service provision has taken place in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">district, so it is not possible to confidently identify where the gaps in provision are.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Transport provision is a huge issue in the district and Clinical Commissioning, Public Health, MIND, Somerset Sight and the Alzheimer's Society all share our concerns</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> about the poor public transport </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">service which is available across a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> large area of our district.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">How effectively do Community Transport services address the needs of passengers in isolated communities?  How could Community Transport be improved?</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">West </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Somerset is fortunate to have nine community car schemes operating in the district, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">run</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> by volunteers, where there is little or no public transport, with the aim of reducing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">individual isolation and providing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> access to healthcare</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and ensuring</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> local familie</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s’ health needs are met</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, where possible</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Accessible Transport West (ATWest</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> - </span><a href="http://www.atwest.org.uk/"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.atwest.org.uk/</span></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) is a community transport service offering wheelchair and accessible transport to residents of West Somerset. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> They provide for those who do not have their own transport or cannot access public transport or car scheme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s due to lack to availability,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> sickness, age or disability.  The services include a SLINKY ‘dial a ride’ door to door service, a car scheme using vol</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">unteers own vehicles, Moor Rover</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (taking local people and tourists with their dogs/bikes to the moor to access linear/circular rights of way) (self-financing), six shopping buses to Minehead and one to Williton (full to capacity – no vacancies at present)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and travel club.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  All users of ATWest services register free of charge and can then access all their services.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Due to the increase in retirement age and the need for people to continue to work, our community transport schemes are finding it much harder to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> recruit volunteer drivers; these services may need additional funding in the future to encourage more drivers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">To what extent should passengers in isolated communities be expected to rely on taxis and other demand-responsive transport service?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Only </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">those residents who can afford to pay for taxi services should be expected to rely on this provision</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, particularly taking into consideration the large distances people have to travel to reach our main service areas</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.  Many of our isolated residents are unable to afford the luxury of a taxi service with the added </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">challenge of having an unknown driver.  For some this can be addressed by using community car scheme service (when available) as the driver is usually a loca</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l person, who is already known to them</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, thereby reducing their perceived vulnerability</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">6</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">What are the main challenges associated with funding transport services in isolated communities?  How can these services be made more affordable?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Costs for providin</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g the service will only increase.  Funding should be based on need </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and allocated to those who do not have sufficient funds to pay for taxi services.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Explore new ways to enable people to get from home to their required destination.  Consider bringing mor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e services to residents rather than them having to travel.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We would be grateful if the above evidence can be taken into consideration by the Transport Committee.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">August 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><sp